ladders.explanation:
This foundation concept explains recursion, a programming technique where a function calls itself to solve smaller instances of a problem. The intuition is divide-and-conquer: break a big problem into similar smaller problems. For example, to generate subsets of n elements, we can generate subsets of n-1 elements and decide whether to include the nth element. Recursion requires two parts: a base case and a recursive case. The base case is the simplest instance that can be solved directly (e.g., when there are no elements left). It stops the recursion to prevent infinite loops. The recursive case reduces the problem size and calls the function again. In subset generation, the base case is when we've processed all elements (index equals array length). The recursive case involves calling the function twice: once excluding the current element, once including it. Time complexity depends on number of recursive calls; here it grows exponentially. Space complexity is the depth of recursion, which is n. This connects to L4 as the underlying principle. Common mistakes include missing base case (causing stack overflow), or not reducing problem size in recursive case. The real pattern is simple recursive definition.

Pseudocode:
def recursive_function(problem):
    if problem is simple enough:  # base case
        return solution
    else:
        smaller_problem = reduce(problem)
        result = recursive_function(smaller_problem)
        return combine(result)
